description:
Project background>> Large-scale land investments by companies, investment funds and private investors increased 10-fold globally between 2006 and 2009, with two-thirds of such investments in sub-Saharan Africa. While largely welcomed by governments, donors and multilateral institutions such as the World Bank for their contribution to employment, technology and knowledge transfer and economic growth, many civil society actors are concerned about the potential social, economic and environmental impacts of such “land grabbing” on local communities, especially women.  These concerns were confirmed by a study of foreign investments in Sierra Leone’s agricultural sector (Oakland Institute, 2011) that revealed various risks and loopholes in four major land acquisitions. It is for these reasons that land governance has become one of the thematic areas of interventions of ICCO Cooperation’s Sierra Leone program, which is undertaken in close collaboration with other local and international partners, including Christian Aid, Cordaid and several ACT members. ICCO’s project partner, Green Scenery, has built up considerable expertise on land grabbing and other social justice issues. 
Project activities and outputs>> Among other activities, the project is contributing to:
- Empirical research investigating the social and economic impact of three major land investments by Addax, Socfin and Siva Biopalm;
- The launch of a civil society platform on land issues, Action for Large Scale Land Acquisition Transparency (ALLAT). ALLAT brings together 11 partners with specific technical expertise and local knowledge in the area of human rights, democracy, environmental issues and community development;
- The creation of a think tank to engage with critical human rights and governance issues relating to large-scale land acquisitions to support the activities of the platform, which include advocacy, sensitization, capacity building, monitoring of land cases, research, networking and the provision of legal services to address the above problems.
